03671nam a22004935i 9780226069753DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20182010ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802260697537 a10.7208/97802260697532doi  a(DE-B1597)523691  a(OCoLC)1039697823  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aJC585 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a320.01/11 aBoym, Svetlana, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAnother Freedom :bThe Alternative History of an Idea /cSvetlana Boym. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (376 p.) :b19 halftones, 2 line drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Freedom versus Liberation: Corrupted Sacrifice from Tragedy to Modernity -- t2. Political and Artistic Freedom in a Cross-Cultural Dialogue -- t3. Liberation with a Birch Rod and the Banality of Terrorism -- t4. Love and Freedom of the Other -- t5. Dissent, Estrangement, and the Ruins of Utopia -- t6. Judgment and Imagination in the Age of Terror -- tConclusion: Freedom and Its Discontents -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe word “freedom” is so overly used—and frequently abused—that it is always in danger of becoming nothing but a cliché. In Another Freedom, Svetlana Boym offers us a refreshing new portrait of the age-old concept. Exploring the rich cross-cultural history of the idea of freedom, from its origins in ancient Greece to the present day, she argues that our attempts to imagine freedom should occupy the space of not only “what is” but also “what if.” Beginning with notions of sacrifice and the emergence of a public sphere for politics and art, Boym expands her account to include the relationships between freedom and liberation, modernity and terror, and political dissent and creative estrangement. While depicting a world of differences, she affirms lasting solidarities based on the commitment to the passionate thinking that reflections on freedom require. To do so, Boym assembles a remarkable cast of characters: Aeschylus and Euripides, Kafka and Mandelstam, Arendt and Heidegger, and a virtual encounter between Dostoevsky and Marx on the streets of Paris. By offering a fresh look at the strange history of this idea, Another Freedom delivers a nuanced portrait of freedom, one whose repercussions will be felt well into the future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aLiberty. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226069753423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226069753.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles